The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Honda hybrid to debut next month
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Honda hybrid to debut next month
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Honda Siel CEO Masahiro Takedagawa in New Delhi on Tuesday. A Telegraph picture                                  
	New Delhi, May 13: Honda Siel Cars India (HSCI) will launch the hybrid version of its sedan Civic by the middle of next month.         
	The hybrid Civic will be the first such car in India. Though we wish to sell very few units, we want our customers to experience this technology, said Masahiro Takedagawa, CEO of Honda Siel.         
	Sources say the half-electric, half-gasoline Civic hybrid will be imported as a completely built unit and will be priced at Rs 20 lakh.         
	The car will switch between the two engines as and when it is required to save fuel.        
	The company today rolled out its eighth generation Accord, eight months after the global launch of the car.        
	The car will be available in three variants  Accord 2.4, Accord 2.4 Elegance and Accord 2.4 Inspire, priced at Rs 16.49 lakh, Rs 16.79 lakh and Rs 17.39 lakh, respectively, for manual transmission. The automatic transmission of the variants are priced between Rs 17.24 lakh and Rs 18.14 lakh.        
	Honda Accord will sport an advanced 2.4l i-VTEC engine. The fuel efficiency of the car has been improved and the engine meets Euro IV emission limits.         
	The company has sold 16,000 units of the Accord in India since its launch in 2001. The Accord, which will be brought in completely knocked down forms, will be assembled at its Greater Noida facility near Delhi.        
	According to Jnaneshwar Sen, vice-president (marketing) of HSCI, while the major components will be imported from the parent company, the car will have a localisation content of 35 per cent.         
	On the companys upcoming plant in Rajasthan, being set up at an investment of $230 million, Sen said it would begin making engine components by September and would roll out cars by the end of 2009.        
	Our new plant will be able to make some engine components by September, while the full assembly line will be ready by next year, said Takedagawa.                                                                                                                                     
